{
  "doc_id": "26468",
  "text": "Klotho is a single-pass transmembrane protein with a long extracellular domain and short cytoplasmic tail that appears to modulate aging [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Despite the specific predominant expression of Klotho in the kidney, parathyroid gland, and choroid plexus of the brain, the extracellular domain of Klotho may be cleaved and released into the blood, cerebrospinal fluid, and urine in a soluble form [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] , presumably allowing Klotho to participate in processes of pleiotropic pathophysiological regulation [CITATION_8] . Overexpression of the Klotho gene extends longevity, while defective Klotho proteins are associated with premature death [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] . Variations in the deoxyribonucleic acid sequences of Klotho have been shown to be associated with various pathologies, including osteoporosis, stroke, and coronary artery disease [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] . Furthermore, these polymorphisms are linked to poor survival in some subsets of patients with advanced chronic kidney disease (CKD) [CITATION_14] [CITATION_15] . Serum soluble Klotho (sKlotho) also possibly plays a role in determining the risk of cardiovascular disease or mortality in some populations and animal models [CITATION_16] [CITATION_17] [CITATION_18] [CITATION_19] [CITATION_20] . However, information regarding the impact of serum sKlotho levels on the clinical characteristics of CKD patients is poor. In the present study, we therefore investigated the predictive significance of varied serum sKlotho levels in chronic hemodialysis (HD) patients in terms of survival and cardiovascular events. International Journal of Endocrinology procedures of the study have been described elsewhere [CITATION_21] . Exclusion criteria for all participants were as follows: active malignancy, pulmonary disease, peritoneal dialysis, death within three months after study entry, and failure to cooperate with the study or provide consent to participate. A total of 63 subjects with archived serum samples available at the point of enrollment were included in the current study. This prospective study was conducted in accordance with the Declaration of Helsinki. The research protocol was approved by the Medical Ethics Committee of Japanese Red Cross Koga Hospital, and all patients provided written informed consent.",
